segments.text: Southwest.
We beat everybody else.
There were dozens and dozens of cities that applied for those, but they didn't have the process we had in place.
They didn't have the action program.

They didn't have the implementation capability that this grant, this grant was probably the purest planning grant I ever saw in my life that was oriented toward away from politics and toward a doing philosophy.
They came back to us, this
apartment of whatever it was at that time, the interiors, it was getting folded into something else.
They came back and they asked if they could use, copy our plan and our program to distribute to other cities to show them how they wanted it to be done.
In essence, it was the model for parking open space planning in the Southwest.
That reminds me of what happened many years before in California when I was with ABAC.
We had our
regional planning process in place at the time that the Title VII open space land grants came into being.
And we applied for them.
Our member cities and our counties applied for them because we had the process in place.
In one calendar year, I was told many years later by an employee of Interior Bureau of Outdoor Recreation that we
got over half of all the funds available in the United States in that one count a year through ABAC.
That's great.
And they didn't want people to know that, of course.
But there you go.
Well, see, we ought to do a better job of letting that be known, of these victories.
We always think these grants are political.
And they have emerged more and more so, it seems like.
But there are times when these windows open up and there's true competition.
And the communities that are doing the planning really reap the benefits from the wars.
I'm trying to get a regional plan process going in the Brazos Valley now, and I'm having some problems, of course, because, oh yeah, it's a tough thing.
But if they get it, and then some of these programs do come along, they'll have something in place and they can move on it immediately.
However, now back to Fort Worth.
What do you find you're doing in Fort Worth that might be different than what you did in Corpus Christi, Galveston, Beaumont, Arlington?
Well, it's completely different.
in the sense that an awful lot of the planning has already been done.

And now what they really need to do is update it, precise it, put it into an implementation mode, and then package it all up into something called a growth management performance system where everybody understands it.
I'm much more involved in the implementation
making something happen than I am in the planning to make it happen.
You know, we've had a cultural district since 1918, 1936, and we're now in the process of trying to make something more happen.
It's evolved naturally down here.
It's quite prestigious, but now we can really use it as a catalyst to do something else.
So it's more into action planning.
We're doing action planning here.
What do you mean by action planning?
Well,

more of taking what we've got and saying okay if this is where we want to be five or ten or twenty years from now what do we do next year to get there what are the steps we take tomorrow next week next month what are some specific things more of a betty crocker cookbook kind of thing you know break the egg then do this do that we're more into into the action planning short-term cost strategic planning if you want this
It's just precising down, dealing with smaller, more manageable issues and concerns within the context that's provided by the overall planning that's gone before this.
Your views.
99.999%, which I buy 100%.
So anyway, what you're talking about in terms of your action plans,
really you're talking about the short range rather than the mid-range or the long range.
Yeah, we're putting more emphasis
on generating short-term and repackaging the mid-range and the long-term.

Repackaging them where they kind of have a fresh look about them and then using that repackaging process to identify these specific actionable items that we can deal with in the short-term to make planning seem more useful, more current, more important to people in the decision-making areas.
Now, are you going to be able to achieve annual review of the comprehensive plan here in Fort Worth like you have elsewhere?
I would be stunned if we couldn't, in particular because it's going to be seen as part of a system as opposed to a product.
When you produce a planning product, there's still that tendency that you've finished it.
If you indicate that it's part of a system and get away from the process and say, no, it's a system here,
People, I think, understand what systems like that clock.
The clock is always moving.
The clock is always turning.

And I think it's going to be very easy for us in a growth management system to insert these modules each year as we update these things and as we pull out these new issues and give them some prominence in the annual work program.
Yeah, if a comprehensive plan document is viewed as sort of a periodic pulling together and documentation of your goals, objectives, and policies, and so forth,
as a part of an ongoing process, and it's going to have to be done periodically, then I think you've got it made.

And you know, one thing we were trying to do in Arlington that was completely different than anywhere else, we were trying to use the new technologies, the computer age here, the microcomputers, for the plan.
We wanted the plan, the product that's called the plan, to be on the computer.
We wanted to have it accessible to everybody in their home.
We wanted the developer to be able to pick up his telephone, plug in his machine, and look at the plan, the goals, the objectives.
We wanted to be able to update that plan daily with new statistics,
New objectives, new council policies from that week.
Type the thing in there.
Don't worry about the latter time of the printing.
Bang!
At the end of the week, it's in the machine.
You can find out what those cities, what the city's goals and objectives and policies and proposals are right there.
Updated daily, if not weekly.
And Ray is still working on that.
I'm not convinced that Arlington won't have the first state-of-the-art comprehensive plan because he's got the knowledge and the technology to make this jump.
We have done a poor, pathetic job of using the computers in the planning profession.
We still got some people that can use them for various little elements or something.
It's like someone telling me, well, now I use my calculator.
Hey, the real value of that thing
for keeping the plants current has not been touched upon in any of the literature I've seen.
And that's what Arlington can do.
That's what we were committed to doing over there.
We're going to take a long time doing it, and I sure as heck was going to do a state-of-the-art one that was going to be technologically superior to anybody else.
What do you want to know about the staff?
Yeah, what about the current planning staff?
Are you up to speed in terms of strength and technical capability and so forth?
We're way understaffed for a city of this size.
We do not have the technical capabilities that a city of this size ought to have.
We have a very, in terms of overall capability, the department's very average.
In fact, I'm kind of surprised by the amount of the averageness.
There's a big average, big group in the middle average.
There's a couple way below average.
There's a couple way above average.
And I would have thought the skewing would have been a little different.
That's something I'm learning.
This is the first time I've been in, somebody might say it's a large city.
I'm kind of surprised that there's not a bigger
grouping above average.
There's just a big mass of average.
We could use more, but effectiveness doesn't depend.
This is out of my book here.
Effectiveness doesn't depend on the size of the staff you have.
It depends on making sure you're doing the right things with the staff that you have.

and it means changing priorities, it means giving up some things we were doing that were taking a lot of time, giving up some things we were doing that weren't taking a lot of time, but just getting rid of them so that you can concentrate your resources and your energies in the areas where you ought to be, in the most protected areas, in the areas with the biggest visibility,
visibility, and in the area where we can be quote, most effective, unquote.
You've got to put your resources where you can be effective.
You can't be everything to everybody.
In this department, the truth is spread out too thin.
One of the things I've been trying to do is get us out of certain businesses.
We've also been trying to do more co-producing.

an old throwback to the self-help days of planning, where you use our technical expertise to advise some citizens who are informed and educated who didn't do a lot of the work themselves, allowing us to serve in almost a consultant role, except allowing us also to take credit for what comes out of this effort and put our name on it, our stamp on it.
Yes, I wanted to ask you what the relationship of the department was now to its citizen base in the community.
We have lost a lot of that citizen base.
They bring it up when they need it.
It's almost like when we recycled the sector plan, we went back out and resurrected the sector councils.
Those councils have now been neglected and allowed to decay.
We don't provide staff support to most of them.
The newsletters are dropping off now.
There's techniques we can do to maintain those contacts and to maintain those groups.
It's hard for them to sustain without issues.
So we have frittered away.
Frittered?
Frittered away.
a valuable resource base out there.
Well, do you mean to reactivate that?
My desire is, but I have to do it as part of the strategy here, that this was a conscious decision on the part of the prior city manager and the council to
to allow these institutions to decay, this kind of benign neglect.
Oh, no, we're all for it.
But if it's not as accurate as it used to be, it wouldn't bother us.
Past councils have taken that attitude.
Yeah.
But you want to turn that around?
Yeah.
And to do that, though, see, I've got
to find the selling point I've got to go back and say and find that glory that goes with the citizen participation.
If we only update those sector plans every eight years then nobody, well why sustain the sector councils over eight years?

But if in fact you get into the annual updating mode then it's obvious that you've got to have these people in place and they've got to be informed and educated and you can't come in and reinvent the wheel each time so you have to have a sustained presence.
That's my strategy, yeah.
And that means staff, staffing.
It means some staff, but it also means taking the staff we have and putting them over into those areas.
And if it's a product, if we can generate enough new products out there that the council says we want to see you doing all of those things,
then maybe over time we get more staff.
But the way it is right now, it's more of a redirect the staff.
Staff has never been the problem.
I mean, it's just like with APA, chapter board of national.
Bob, it's not staff, it's not money.
It's doing something with what you have.
It's a bias for action.
It's putting your resources where they can make a difference and cutting them in areas where it doesn't.
See, National was the same way.
I tried to cut the budget up there, nobody could do it.
We couldn't do it.
There's always somebody wanting to protect that thing.
It's the way it is here in city government.
Somebody always wants to protect something out there.
So I tell these people, we're just not telling anybody we're not doing it.
We just quit doing it.
Don't go out there and tell somebody.
Don't confront them.
I'm not doing it anymore.
I'll tell the council, we want to cut out this thing.
We just quit doing it.
And heck, I got news for them.
Nobody's going to miss it.
Yeah.
If it's been ineffective, who's going to care?
That's right.
Okay, well, Bruce, good luck in your relatively new position here.
And we will be watching all of your successes as they appear one by one in the future.
And thank you very much for your time again.
And as I told you at the beginning of this interview, if you move again to another city, this is your last interview.
Okay.
So stay around a while, please.
I'll move here again.
It won't be a big city.
It probably won't be in Texas.
I'm going to get out of this planning business here one of these days, if I'm lucky.
Thank you very much.
You're welcome.
